. Claiming to be guided by the voices of the saints, she persuaded the French dauphin to defy the occupying English forces and have himself crowned, and she led the French army that raised the siege of Orleans in  1429 . The following year she was captured by the Burgundians and sold to the English, and a year later she was burned at the stake for witchcraft at the age of 18 or 19. Her story has captured the imagination of many writers, and she is variously portrayed as a national and political hero, a model of apolitical straightforwardness and honesty, and a religious heroine. She was canonized in  1920 . More recent influences have included the American film actress  Joan Crawford  (  1908–77 , born  Lucille le Sueur ), the British actress  Joan Collins  (  b. 1933 ), the American comedienne  Joan Rivers  (  b. 1933 ), and the West Indian pop singer  Joan Armatrading  (  b. 1950 )."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When John d'Eylesford of Tillington was born before 1335, his father, Edmund De Eylesford, was 32 and his mother, Mrs. Edmund de Eyelesford, was 32. He married Isabel de la Barre about 1354, in Tillington, Herefordshire, England. They were the parents of at least 1 son. He died in 1368, in Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom."},"et":{"before 1335–1368":"enne 1335–1368","1331–1346":"1331–1346","1335–1368":"1335–1368","1337–1421":"1337–1421","1354–1424":"1354–1424","1355–1395":"1355–1395","1302–1337":"1302–1337","1303–Female":"1303–Surnud","before 1335":"enne 1335","1395":"1395","1337":"1337","1303":"1303","1424":"1424","1368":"1368","1302":"1302","1335":"1335","1346":"1346","Abt 1355":"umbes 1355","1355":"1355","1421":"1421","about 1325":"umbes 1325","1354":"1354","1331":"1331","about 1354":"umbes 1354","Tillington, Burghill, Herefordshire, England, United Kingdom":"Burghill, Herefordshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tillington, Gloucestershire, England, United Kingdom":"Gloucestershire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Tillington, Herefordshire, Englan